During the year of income, did the Superannuation Entity have contribution arrears?

If the superannuation fund is an industry fund, and there are one or more employer sponsors who are deemed to be in arrears by the superannuation entity (even taking into consideration the superannuation guarantee requirements), a Y response should be reported.
Materiality does not apply to this item. A Y response should be given in all cases where the superannuation entity had contribution arrears during the reporting period, regardless of how large the arrears were.
During the year of income, did the Superannuation Entity have a contribution holiday (applicable only to defined benefit funds)?

This item is only applicable to defined benefit funds. If the superannuation entity is not a defined benefit fund, then an N response should be provided at this item.
Materiality does not apply to this item. A Y response should be given in all cases where the superannuation entity had a contribution holiday during the reporting period, regardless of how small the defined benefit entity is.
Where investment choice is offered by the Superannuation Entity, how many investment strategy choices are offered?

A superannuation entity should include all investment strategy options available across the entity, even when they are not available to all members.
If there are sub-plans, report the sub-plan with the largest number of options.

Where investment choice is offered by the Superannuation Entity, what value of member funds have been placed in the default investment strategy as a result of the member not selecting an investment strategy?

Where failure to nominate is not recorded in an entity's system, the superannuation entity should either: - disclose an estimate; or - report the total value of the default investment strategy. Entities with sub-plans should report the default value for their largest sub-plan.
